(44, 2, 22, 58, 2, 4, 4, 'miracles and wonders and signs', 'Connection of Signs and Wonders', 'Both passages emphasize the role of signs and wonders in validating God''s message. Acts 2:22 highlights Jesus'' miracles, while Hebrews 2:4 mentions God bearing witness through signs and wonders.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 42, 22, 22, 22, 'determinate counsel', 'Divine Determination in Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of divine determination in the events leading to Jesus'' crucifixion. Acts 2:23 mentions ''determinate counsel'' while Luke 22:22 states ''as it was determined,'' linking the foreknowledge of God to the betrayal and crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 44, 4, 28, 28, 'determinate counsel and foreknowledge of God', 'Divine Foreknowledge and Counsel', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of God''s predetermined plan. Acts 2:23 mentions God''s ''determinate counsel and foreknowledge,'' while Acts 4:28 refers to ''thy hand and thy counsel determined before.''', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 1, 50, 20, 20, NULL, 'Divine Purpose in Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s sovereignty in human actions. Both passages emphasize that what is intended for evil can ultimately serve God''s purpose for good.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 23, 46, 10, 11, 'counsel', 'Divine Counsel and Foreknowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s counsel and foreknowledge in both passages. Acts 2:23 speaks of God''s determinate counsel in the crucifixion of Jesus, while Isaiah 46:10-11 emphasizes God''s ability to declare His counsel and purpose from the beginning.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 44, 3, 18, 18, 'by the determinate counsel and foreknowledge of God', 'Fulfillment of Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize God''s foreknowledge and the fulfillment of prophecy regarding Christ''s suffering. Acts 2:23 mentions God''s determinate counsel, while Acts 3:18 refers to what God showed through the prophets, linking the two ideas of divine plan and fulfillment.', 'prophecy', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 60, 1, 20, 20, 'foreknowledge of God', 'Foreknowledge and Foreordination Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of foreknowledge and foreordination in relation to Jesus'' crucifixion. Acts 2:23 speaks of God''s determinate counsel, while 1 Peter 1:20 refers to Jesus being foreordained before the foundation of the world.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 23, 40, 26, 24, 24, 'foreknowledge of God', 'Connection of Betrayal and Foreknowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the predetermined nature of Jesus'' betrayal and crucifixion. Acts 2:23 speaks of God''s foreknowledge in delivering Jesus, while Matthew 26:24 highlights the inevitability of betrayal as written.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 46, 6, 14, 14, 'God hath raised up', 'Resurrection Power Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s power in resurrection. Acts 2:24 states that Jesus was raised, while 1 Corinthians 6:14 affirms that God will also raise believers, highlighting a shared theme of divine resurrection.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 44, 2, 32, 32, 'God hath raised up', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize God''s action in raising Jesus from the dead. Acts 2:24 states it was not possible for death to hold Him, while Acts 2:32 affirms that God raised Him up, with witnesses to this event.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 60, 1, 21, 21, NULL, 'Resurrection and Faith Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of God raising Jesus from the dead, linking the resurrection to the foundation of faith and hope in God. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' resurrection as central to belief.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 51, 2, 12, 12, 'having loosed the pains of death', 'Resurrection and New Life', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection, highlighting that God raised Jesus from the dead. Acts 2:24 speaks of Jesus being loosed from death, while Colossians 2:12 connects believers'' baptism to being raised with Him.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 45, 6, 4, 4, 'loosed the pains of death', 'Resurrection and New Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection, as both passages discuss Christ''s victory over death and the implications for believers. Acts 2:24 emphasizes that death could not hold Christ, while Romans 6:4 illustrates how believers share in this resurrection, leading to a new life.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 45, 8, 11, 11, NULL, 'Resurrection and Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection, highlighting God''s power to raise Jesus from the dead and the promise of life for believers through the Spirit. This connection illustrates the continuity of resurrection as a central concept in Christian faith.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 24, 43, 10, 18, 18, 'loosed the pains of death', 'Resurrection Power and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the power over death. Acts 2:24 states that death could not hold Jesus, while John 10:18 highlights His authority to lay down and take up His life again.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 19, 16, 8, 11, 'he is on my right hand', 'Connection of Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of setting the Lord before oneself and His presence at the right hand, which provides stability and joy. This connection highlights the assurance of not being moved due to divine support.', 'theme', 0.706, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 23, 41, 13, 13, 'right hand', 'Divine Support and Presence', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine support, as both passages emphasize the presence of God in times of need. In Acts, David speaks of the Lord being at his right hand, while Isaiah reassures that God will hold the right hand of His people.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 19, 62, 6, 6, 'that I should not be moved', 'Divine Support and Stability', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine support and stability. Acts 2:25 reflects David''s assurance in God''s presence, while Psalms 62:6 expresses trust in God as a rock and defense, leading to a sense of being unshaken.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 23, 50, 7, 9, 'I foresaw the Lord always before my face', 'Divine Support and Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine support and confidence in God''s presence. Acts 2:25 reflects David''s assurance of God''s nearness, while Isaiah 50:7-9 expresses a similar conviction of God''s help and justification.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 44, 13, 32, 36, 'I foresaw the Lord always before my face', 'Connection Between David and Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus and its fulfillment of Davidic promises. Acts 2:25 references David''s assurance in God''s presence, while Acts 13:32-36 connects David''s lineage to Jesus'' resurrection, highlighting the continuity of God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 25, 44, 2, 29, 30, 'I foresaw the Lord always before my face', 'Connection of David and Christ', 'Both passages emphasize David''s prophetic role regarding Christ. Acts 2:25 mentions David''s foresight, while Acts 2:29-30 highlights his prophecy about Christ''s resurrection and kingship.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
